Population Density around Stations - ETL Workflow

Introduction

In this workflow, we will create a shapefile that classifies each station on the Minneapolis Green Line Extension (GLE) by population and by population density within its catchment area. This will be accomplished using open portal data (for stations), OpenStreetMap network data (to create network-based catchment areas, or isochrones), and U.S. Census Bureau data (for population counts). For reference, a map of the GLE is provided below.

Figure 1: The route map of the Green Line Extension (GLE) (Source: Route and Stations, n.d.)

ETL workflow diagram

Figure 2: ELT workflow for calculating population and population density around stations

View static image in case embedded flowchart doesnt work Figure 2a: ETL workflow in static image format

Environment setup

First, we will load in all needed packages:

library(sf)

Extract

For this workflow, three data sources are needed:

  • Station data from the Minnesota Geospatial Commons (Metropolitan Council 2022)
    • To be downloaded directly from the data portal
  • Street network data from OpenStreetMap, in order to create isochrones (OpenStreetMap Contributors 2022)
    • To be accessed indirectly through the openrouteservice package
  • Population data from the US Census Bureau (U.S. Census Bureau 2010)
    • To be accessed through the tidycensus package
    • Geographical data to be accessed through the tigris package, as tidycensus failed to load 2010 block geometry

Station data - from Minnesota Geospatial Commons

First, we must extract the locations of the planned Green Line stations, as well as the route of the Green Line itself for visualization purposes. These data are available from the Minnesota Geospatial Commons, but can also be downloaded directly from R. Downloading and unzipping lines were commented, as they have already been run.

# download.file(url = "https://resources.gisdata.mn.gov/pub/gdrs/data/pub/us_mn_state_metc/trans_transitways_generalized/shp_trans_transitways_generalized.zip", destfile = "stations.zip")
# unzip(zipfile = "stations.zip", exdir = "stations")

# Read station and line shapefiles
RAW_stations <- read_sf("stations/TransitwayStationsGeneralizedLocations.shp")
RAW_lines <- read_sf("stations/TransitwayAlignmentsGeneralized.shp")

Street network data

Because openrouteservices is able to access OpenStreetMap remotely, no street network data must be loaded directly into the R environment.

Based on the list above, it seems that P001001 is the correct variable. We thus extract this variable for all Hennepin County blocks in the 2010 decennial census.

RAW_block_pop <- get_decennial(geography = "block",
                         variables = c(pop = "P001001"),
                         county = "Hennepin",
                         state = "MN",
                         year = 2010,
                         survey = "acs5",
                         geometry = FALSE,
                         output = "wide")

Finally, we use tigris to acquire census block geometry, as my attempts to include geometry through tidycensus did not succeed.

RAW_block_geom <- blocks(state = "MN", county = "hennepin", year = 2010)

Transform

In this section, the following operations are conducted:

  • Subset stations and routes to only include the GLE
  • Create isochrones around stations
  • Merge census data to census geographies
  • Interpolate population within station isochrones based on census data
  • Calculate area of each isochrone, then use as a denominator for population to calculate population density
  • Merge population and population density variables back to each station

From the tables above, it appears that we only need to include rows in RAW_stations where Serves is GreenExt,1 and rows in RAW_lines where NameTransi is Green Line Extension. The dplyr filter function will be used to do this.

GLE_stations <- RAW_stations %>% filter(Serves == "GreenExt")
GLE_line <- RAW_lines %>% filter(NameTransi == "Green Line Extension")

Before moving on, we should quickly view the result to make sure that it matches up with Figure 1 above.

# Set tmap mode to interactive viewing
tmap_mode("view")
## tmap mode set to interactive viewing
# Create map
tm_shape(GLE_line) + tm_lines() +
  tm_shape(GLE_stations) + tm_dots()

Figure 3: The route and stations of the GLE, as extracted and filtered from the Minnesota Geospatial Commons

The resulting map does appear to match Figure 1.

Street network data - isochrones

The next step is to create isochrones around each station. They are like buffers, but based on actual street network distances, rather than Euclidean distance. Thus, areas that are nearby stations but are inaccessible by road networks will not be included.

However, for openrouteservice to be able to calculate isochrones, the data must be transformed into EPSG:4326.

GLE_stations1 <- st_transform(GLE_stations, 4326)
GLE_line1 <- st_transform(GLE_line, 4326)

Next, we create isochrones using the coordinates of the stations.2 Walking distances are set to 400 meters, which is roughly equivalent to 1/4 mile, a fairly common buffer distance used in public transportation research (as per my literature review).

Unfortunately, we can only calculate 5 at a time due to API limitations. Thus, we have to run ors_isochrones in four batches, fix the indices of each batch so they do not overlap, and then bind them together. Finally, we have to make the geometry of the isochrones valid with st_make_valid, as one isochrones geometry does not produce a valid shape.

i1 <- ors_isochrones(st_coordinates(GLE_stations1[1:5, ]), profile = "foot-walking", range_type = "distance", range = 400, output = "sf")
i2 <- ors_isochrones(st_coordinates(GLE_stations1[6:10, ]), profile = "foot-walking", range_type = "distance", range = 400, output = "sf")
i3 <- ors_isochrones(st_coordinates(GLE_stations1[11:15, ]), profile = "foot-walking", range_type = "distance", range = 400, output = "sf")
i4 <- ors_isochrones(st_coordinates(GLE_stations1[16, ]), profile = "foot-walking", range_type = "distance", range = 400, output = "sf")

# Make index values unique
i2$group_index <- i2$group_index + 5
i3$group_index <- i3$group_index + 10
i4$group_index <- i4$group_index + 15

# Bind rows together and fix an invalid geometry
GLE_isochrones <- rbind(i1, i2, i3, i4) %>% st_make_valid()

  tm_shape(GLE_stations1) + tm_dots() +

Population data

Before we can assign census data to the isochrones, we need to merge our census data to our census geographies. This can be done simply with the merge` function. Extraneous columns are removed for simplicity. To avoid geographic overlay issues with isochrones, we will also transform the CRS to EPSG:4326.

# Merge census geographies to census data, and then convert to sf object
MERGED_block <- merge(RAW_block_pop[ , c("GEOID", "pop")], RAW_block_geom[ , c("GEOID10")], by.x = "GEOID", by.y = "GEOID10") %>% st_as_sf()

# Transform CRS
MERGED_block1 <- st_transform(MERGED_block, 4326)

Now that we have one object containing both census block population and geography, we can assign population values to each isochrone through interpolation. We will use spatially extensive interpolation (a sum of unstandardized counts), as our goal is to approximate the total population within each isochrone.3

GLE_isochrones_interpolated <- st_interpolate_aw(MERGED_block1["pop"], GLE_isochrones, ext = TRUE)
## Warning in st_interpolate_aw.sf(MERGED_block1["pop"], GLE_isochrones, ext =
## TRUE): st_interpolate_aw assumes attributes are constant or uniform over areas
## of x

In order to make population data spatially intensive, we have to divide the population of each isochrone by the isochrones area.

# Calculate area of each isochrone in km^2
GLE_isochrones_interpolated$area <- st_area(GLE_isochrones_interpolated) %>% set_units(km^2)

# Calculate population density per km^2
GLE_isochrones_interpolated$popDensKM2 <- GLE_isochrones_interpolated$pop / GLE_isochrones_interpolated$area

Putting it all together - merging isochrone data back to stations

Unfortunately, due to limitations in the openrouteservices package, station identifiers could not be kept when creating isochrones, and thus data from the isochrones will have to be joined back to the stations spatially. We can use the operation st_nearest_feature, which matches a point either to an isochrone it is within, or to the nearest isochrone available (necessary because not all stations exist on road networks, and thus may be excluded from their own isochrones).

MERGED_stations <- st_join(GLE_stations1, GLE_isochrones_interpolated, join = st_nearest_feature)

Finally, we can place the geometry column last and remove unnecessary columns with dplyr functions.

MERGED_stations <- MERGED_stations %>%
  relocate(geometry, .after = popDensKM2) %>%
  select(-MapLabel, -Serves, -Shared, -PointUniqu)
